<abstract>
	<para>
		<application>gtranslator</application> is a comfortable editor
		for the gettext po files which are mostly the basis for i18n
		in GNOME and other desktop environments.
	</para>
</abstract>

</artheader>

<sect1 id="introduction">
	<title>Introduction</title>
		<para>
			<application>gtranslator</application> offers you many 
			comfortable dialogs to edit the po files fields.
		</para>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="features">
	<title>Major features of <application>gtranslator</application></title>
		<para>
			gtranslator has got many features which are 
			<emphasis>useful</emphasis>
			for editing the gettext po files. The major features are:
			<itemizedlist>
				<listitem>
					<para>Crashless and quick editing of
					gettext po files</para>
				</listitem>	
				<listitem>
					<para>Very low memory usage (about only
					<emphasis>950KB with</emphasis> a po 
					file parsed and displayed)</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Navigation inside the fuzzy,
					untranslated and translated
					messages</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Regular expressions based
					find/search function</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Compile function for testing
					your po files</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Status indication with detailed
					information at the statusbar and a
					<emphasis>useful and correct</emphasis>
					progress bar</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Advanced history list with
					<emphasis>
						project name and version
					</emphasis>
					instead of only showing
					the filename</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Opening of gzip'ed and compiled
					(.mo/.gmo) gettext po files</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Opening of remote po files via
					GnomeVFS (and http, ftp, nfs and other
					access routines of GnomeVFS).</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Editing with the help of a
					"special char" instead of only hardly
					recognizable free spaces</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Update function to update the po
					file with the (if installed)
					xml-i18n-tools</para>
				</listitem>
			</itemizedlist>
		</para>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="use-of-gtranslator">
	<title>Usual use of <application>gtranslator</application></title>
		<para>
			<application>gtranslator</application> is normally used
			to edit gettext po files (and the various metamorhoses of
			po files like gzip'ed po files and compiled po files).
		</para>
		
		<para>
			<application>gtranslator</application> allows you to open
			a po file directly within the command line as a argument
			like 
			<emphasis>
				gtranslator filename
			</emphasis>
			or
			<emphasis>
				gtranslator http://remotehost/filename
			</emphasis>
			or
			<emphasis>
				gtranslator ftp://ftphost/filename
			</emphasis>.	
		</para>

		<para>
			After doing your translation work you can save your file
			<emphasis>but</emphasis> do not forget that gtranslator
			is for now vamping your currently not needed translations
			(these are the strings/lines in the po files starting
			with #~) before you save it.
</sect1>

<sect1 id="commandlinearguments">
	<title>Command line arguments</title>
		<para>
			<application>gtranslator</application> understands some
			command line arguments:
			<itemizedlist>
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--help</emphasis> Shows you a
					litte help message on the command line.
					</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--version</emphasis> Tells you
					the version of <application>gtranslator
					</application> you're using.
					</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--display</emphasis> Let's you
					define the display to start 
					<application>gtranslator</application>
					on.
					</para>
				</listitem>	
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--webalize</emphasis> Prints
					out a htmlized output file (you must
					give the html output filename as the
					next argument) of the po file.
					</para>
					<para>
					An example call would be:
					<emphasis>
					<application>gtranslator</application>
					--webalize=Evolution.html tr.po
					</emphasis>
					</para>
				</listitem>	
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--geometry</emphasis> Let's
					you define a standard geometry string
					to which the gtranslator window will
					conform.
					</para>
					<para>
					An example call would be:
					<emphasis>
					<application>gtranslator</application>
					--geometry="320x240+0+0" tr.po
					</emphasis>
					(This opens gtranslator at "+0+0", the
					left upper corner, with a size of 
					320x240).
					</para>
				</listitem>	
			</itemizedlist>	
		</para>
</sect1>

